It is hard, but I am lucky that I have the strength in my life to walk the distance and sometimes I have to go with my mother to find the food. I am not talking about the food on the tree and everything, but I have to go to find the food to cook. This is my only concern for me in Kiribati.(id)

Because Kiribati is an archipelago, every island is experiencing climate change in its own way and accordingly pursue their own, adapted solutions. Only because of this, a coherent political discourse on this island state is hardly possible, also due to other reasons, such as strong religious influences. From a politico-ecological perspective, however, the conversation with the young descendants of the original inhabitants of this country is worth it, not least because their experience and experience of the climate crisis is more credible than that of their elders who have witnessed the expansion of the rapidly growing Western way of life into their country. Their eloquence and commitment are inspiring, as the following video of one of the seven children who took part demonstrates, as well as their sheer willingness to accept and carry on what the actors on their island dictate (without being able to significantly influence these processes):
